{
  "topicId": "m5-t1",
  "title": "Asking About the Location of Things (فين؟)",
  "dialect": "egyptian-arabic",
  "steps": [
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Introducing 'Where is/are?' (فين؟)",
          "arabic": "تقديم 'أين؟' (فين؟)"
        },
        "text": "The most common way to ask 'Where is...?' or 'Where are...?' in Egyptian Arabic is by using the word 'فين؟'. Unlike English, you don't always need an explicit verb 'is' or 'are' in the sentence. You simply place 'فين؟' before or after the noun you're asking about.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "فين الكِتَاب؟",
            "english": "Where is the book?",
            "transliteration": "Feen el-ketāb?",
            "diacriticalNotes": "The word 'الكِتَاب' (el-ketāb) refers to 'the book'."
          },
          {
            "arabic": "القَهْوَة فين؟",
            "english": "Where is the coffee?",
            "transliteration": "El-ʾahwa feen?",
            "diacriticalNotes": "The word 'القَهْوَة' (el-ʾahwa) means 'the coffee'."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Basic Nouns: Objects",
          "arabic": "أسماء أساسية: أشياء"
        },
        "text": "Let's learn some basic object nouns that we can ask about. Remember, 'ال' (el) is the definite article 'the'.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "كِتَاب",
            "english": "book",
            "transliteration": "ketāb"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "قَلَم",
            "english": "pen/pencil",
            "transliteration": "ʾalam"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "شَنطة",
            "english": "bag",
            "transliteration": "shanta"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "مِفْتَاح",
            "english": "key",
            "transliteration": "moftāḥ"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Combining 'فين' with Nouns",
          "arabic": "دمج 'فين' مع الأسماء"
        },
        "text": "Now, let's put 'فين؟' together with the nouns we just learned to form simple questions.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "فين القَلَم؟",
            "english": "Where is the pen?",
            "transliteration": "Feen el-ʾalam?"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "فين الشَنطة؟",
            "english": "Where is the bag?",
            "transliteration": "Feen esh-shanta?"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "المِفْتَاح فين؟",
            "english": "Where is the key?",
            "transliteration": "El-moftāḥ feen?"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "practice-sentence",
      "sentence": {
        "arabic": "فين الكِتَاب بتاعي؟",
        "english": "Where is my book?",
        "transliteration": "Feen el-ketāb betāʿī?"
      },
      "context": "Using 'بتَاعي' (betāʿī) for 'my'."
    },
    {
      "type": "practice-sentence",
      "sentence": {
        "arabic": "القَلَم ده فين؟",
        "english": "Where is this pen?",
        "transliteration": "El-ʾalam da feen?"
      },
      "context": "Using 'ده' (da) for 'this' (masculine)."
    },
